@node intro "Introduction"

Introduction
============

Cranu is a GUI for various archivers available for AmigaOS. It allows you to
quickly and easily create archives from a comfortable GUI. It comes with profiles
for LhA, LZX, Zip, Tar/GZip and Tar/BZip2. It is possible to create profiles
for other archivers and distribute them seperately to Cranu itself!

@endnode

@node requi "Requirements"

Requirements
============

Cranu requires:

* AmigaOS 4.x
* At least one supported archiver program installed and in the searchpath

@endnode

@node insta "Installation"

Installation
============

Copy the Cranu executable to your hard disk. You have to copy the "Profiles"
directory to the exact same place as you copy the executable.

If you want to install third party profiles, copy them to the profiles
directory. They MUST have the extension ".cranu".

@endnode

@node usage "Usage"

Usage
=====

Using Cranu is very simple. Here is a step-by-step guide to creating an
archive:

1) Load Cranu by clicking its icon
2) Use the "Archive File" gadget to specify the archive file to create
3) Select the archive format with the drop-down gadget next to the filename
4) Find and highlight files to archive in the left file browser
5) Click ">" to add them to the archive
6) Click Start

and you're done!

If you select files in different directories, the directory structure will
be maintained. For example, if you navigated to:

"Work:Some/Directory/Blah"

then added the files "a", "b" and "c", then went up a level to
"Work:Some/Directory" and added the files "d" and "e", the archive contents
lister would look like this:

Blah/a
Blah/b
Blah/c
d
e

You can even add files across partitions! If you had an archive like this:

Work:a
Work:directory/b
Workbench:another/dir/c

the final archive would contain:

Work/a
Work/directory/b
Workbench/another/dir/c

Note, that when archiving files in more than one directory, the files will be
copied to a temporary directory before being archived. See @{ "configuration" LINK "confi" }
for instructions on how to set the location of that directory.

Normally, Cranu archives files from as far into the directory tree as possible.
For example, if you added the following files:

Work:dir1/dir2/dir3/a
Work:dir1/dir2/dir3/b
Work:dir1/dir2/dir3/c
Work:dir1/dir2/dir3/dir4/d
Work:dir1/dir2/dir3/dir4/e

The archive would contain:

a
b
c
dir4/d
dir4/e

But you may want to include dir3, or dir2. Since 0.2, Cranu includes "<" and
">" buttons under the archive lister. Click "<" to archive from earlier in the
directory tree, and ">" to archive from later.

For the above example, clicking "<" once would create an archive containing:

dir3/a
dir3/b
dir3/c
dir3/dir4/d
dir3/dir4/e

Clicking "<" again would also include "dir2" etc. etc. Clicking ">" will have
the opposite effect.

Finally, if an archiver supports it, you can opt to only add files without the
archive bit set (and set the bit as it archives). Note, though, that if you
archive files from multiple partitions, the archive bit WON'T be set, since
the files are being archived from a temporary copy, and that temporary copy
will be updated instead.
@endnode

@node confi "Configuration"

Configuration
=============

To configure Cranu, select "Settings -> General". There are two options in this
window.

The first box is for the temporary directory. This directory is @{b}created@{ub}
when archiving files across partitions. You should specify a directory that can
be safely created and then completely deleted here, for example "T:Cranu" and *NOT*
"T:" for example.

The second box specifies the maximum size (in megabytes) that is allowed to be
put into the temporary directory. Note, though, that if a single file exceeds
this file size, it will be copied in its entirety to the temporary dir.

The temporary directory is ONLY used if you are archiving files across partitions.

You can also configure archiver profiles, but this is covered in the
@{"creating profiles" LINK "cprof"} section.
@endnode

@node cprof "Creating profiles"

Creating profiles
=================

Cranu uses external profiles for each archiver, so you can easily add support
for more archive formats, or just customise the way existing formats are used.

From the main window, select the "Settings->Archivers" option to bring up the
window.

For each profile, you specify the following options:

1) Profile name

This is just how the program refers to the archive format in dialog boxes etc.


2) File extension

This is the file extension for this archive format (for example .lha for LhA)


3) Normal command

This is the command to call when adding files to an archive normally. "%a"
will be replaced with the archive name, and "%f" will be replaced with
filenames to add. The filenames will be in quotes and seperated by spaces.
Use "%%" to insert a percent symbol, if need be.


4) Arc. bit command

This is the command to call when adding files to an archive, respecting the
archive bit. It has the same format as the normal command.


5) Max. files/call

This is the maximum number of files to pass to the archiver per call. Setting
it to zero tries to archive all the files in one call to the archiver.

1, 2, 3 and 5 are compulsory fields.

You can create new profiles with the "Add" button. The profiles are all saved
to disk when you close the Archiver preferences window. They are stored in the
"Profiles" subdirectory, which should be in the same place as the Cranu
executable.

If you "remove" a profile, it is simply renamed with ".disabled" on the end.
You can restore it by renaming it and restarting Cranu.
@endnode

@node bugs "Known Bugs"

Known Bugs
==========

* Adding files in "archive bit mode" doesn't set the archive bit if the files
  are across partitions.

@endnode

@node todo "History / ToDo"

History
=======

0.1 BETA (8th Feb 2006)

  · First release


0.2 BETA (11th Feb 2006)

  · Removed debug accidentally left in 0.1
  · If adding a large directory takes longer than 2 seconds, a progress window
    now appears so you can see the program is working. It also contains an
    abort button
  · Added the ability to archive files from higher in the directory tree


0.3 BETA (18th Feb 2006)

  · Double clicking in the filebrowser now only opens a directory if the same one
    was highlighted for both clicks
  · The "Abort" gadget on the progress requester now actually works


0.3.1 BETA (18th Feb 2006)

  · Now has a proper Amiga version string (thanks to David Rey for pointing this
    out)

0.4 BETA (12 Mar 2006)

  · Localised (no translations yet...)
  · The main window is now an "AppWindow". Icons can be dragged onto it
    and they will be added to the archive list.
  · Scrollwheel support
  


ToDo
====

Suggestions (note: Suggestions from PayPal donators will carry more weight ;-)

